Not quite metaprogramming, but definitely hosting configuration outside of the dataclass itself so one can consolidate logic around `to_dict()` `to_json()` without having to subclass or add additional layers of handling.

An example - if I was returning the dataclass from a web endpoint, and wanted a user to be able to supply which fields they wanted as parameters, I could do something like:

```python
from flask import request

def is_report_field(k, v):
    return k in request.parameters.split(",")

# ...

@dataclass
class Report(DataClassJsonMixin)
    summary: str = field(metadata=config(exclude=is_report_field))
```
While it isn't a use-case I care about, if we were to go with the value-only predicate initially, and then later decide that the key name would be nice to have, this would be difficult to manage without a breaking API change. 

